Thus closes Ayala's second chapter, in which without much arrangement he has disburdened his mind of the general matter which he most desired to impress on his contemporaries, aud has left himself free to enter on the topics of detail which follow. It should have shielded him from the imputation of neglecting the Just causes of war, by making which Grotius showed that even his prodigious memory was not infallible.
